
Key Takeaway
Declarative (Terraform) → You say what you want, Terraform ensures it happens.

Imperative (Scripts) → You say how to do it, step by step, which is more error‑prone and less scalable.

┌───────────────────────────────┬────────────────────────────────┐
│       Declarative (Terraform) │       Imperative (Scripts)     │
├───────────────────────────────┼────────────────────────────────┤
│ Define the desired end state  │ Define step‑by‑step actions    │
│ ("I want 3 servers + LB")     │ ("Create server → configure →  │
│                               │ install load balancer → link") │
├───────────────────────────────┼────────────────────────────────┤
│ Terraform figures out how to  │ Engineer must specify every    │
│ reach that state automatically│ command in exact order         │
├───────────────────────────────┼────────────────────────────────┤
│ Idempotent: repeat runs give  │ Risk of drift: repeated runs   │
│ consistent results            │ may cause errors or duplicates │
├───────────────────────────────┼────────────────────────────────┤
│ Version‑controlled, reusable  │ Harder to track changes, often │
│ configs stored in Git         │ scattered across scripts       │
├───────────────────────────────┼────────────────────────────────┤
│ Cloud‑agnostic: works across  │ Usually tied to one platform   │
│ AWS, Azure, GCP, etc.         │ or environment                 │
└───────────────────────────────┴────────────────────────────────┘
